properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for for coastal water from Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border.

  • The levels of blue green algae within the Gippsland Lakes have decreased to below safe contact thresholds. The entire Gippsland Lakes system and ocean is now safe for recreational contact with the water.
  • It is important to note that advice regarding the consumption of specific seafood remains in place.
  • The latest seafood sample results show that Nodularin concentrations remain elevated in crab and bug samples collected within and outside the Gippsland Lakes. Additional seafood samples are being organised for collection and analysis.
Do not eat prawns from affected waters.

These prawns may have come from the Gippsland Lakes and Ninety Mile Beach area and may contain toxins from the recent blue green algae bloom.

Do to not consume prawns caught within 10 nautical miles of the shore between Mcloughlins Beach and the Victoria-New South Wales border.
What you should do:
  • Visit betterhealth.vic.gov.au for more information. 
  • Keep up-to-date with algae information at www.water.vic.gov.au/waterways-and-catchments/rivers-estuaries-andwaterways/blue-green-algae 

Protect your health:
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 19/10/2022 03:40 pm or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter.
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Loddon River. 

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LODDON WEIR

MINOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT DOWNSTREAM LAANECOORIE RESRVOIR AND APPIN SOUTH 

MODERATE FLOODING LIKELY ALONG THE LODDON RIVER FROM THURSDAY

River levels are easing in upper parts of the Loddon River catchment, however, elevated river levels with minor to moderate flooding is continuing in parts of the Loddon River as floodwaters travel downstream through the catchment. Minor flooding is continuing along the Loddon River at Downstream Laanecoorie Reservoir and Appin South. Moderate flooding is occurring at Downstream Loddon Weir. In the 24 hours to 3:00 pm Tuesday, no significant rainfall has been observed across the Loddon River catchment. Heavy rainfall is forecast from Wednesday evening which is likely to cause renewed widespread moderate flooding across the Loddon River catchment from Thursday morning.

Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang

Minor flooding is occurring along the Loddon River at Appin South. At Downstream Loddon Weir, moderate flooding is occurring and the river level is steady. Minor flooding is continuing along the Loddon River at Appin South.The Loddon River at Appin South is currently at 2.97 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) for the next few days. Further river levels rises are likely as upstream floodwaters arrive.The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is currently at 76.64 (m AHD) metres and steady, below the minor flood level (77.00 m AHD). The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is expected to remain below the minor flood level (77.00 m) for the next few days. Further river levels rises are likely as upstream floodwaters arrive.


Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Avoid any contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • People camping, living, or working along rivers and creeks should be ready to relocate or move to higher ground should flooding develop.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads and bridges may be impacted by floodwater.
  • Low-lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be impacted by floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 12/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Initial Flood Watch for Northern and parts of Southern Victoria 

WIDESPREAD MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED ACROSS THE FLOOD WATCH AREA, MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY IN SOME CATCHMENTS FROM THURSDAY
 
Showers and rain are expected from Wednesday as a cold front moves into the west of the state. The rain will continue during Thursday and Friday, with heavy falls likely as the front moves slowly eastwards. 

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments. 

From Wednesday to Friday, rainfall totals of 60-100 mm are forecast north of the divide, while rainfall totals of 30-60 mm are forecast south of the divide 

Minor to moderate flooding is expected across the flood watch areas. Major flooding is likely in some catchments. Catchments likely to be affected include:

Mitchell River 
Macalister River 
Thomson River 
Latrobe River 
South Gippsland Rivers

MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.   

Downstream along the Murray River, moderate flooding continues at Corowa, Torrumbarry and Barham.

properties.webBody:
This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek.

  • A landslide has occurred on the Bogong - High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
  • There is a slow moving active landslide on Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Regional Roads Victoria has undertaken geotechnical investigations at the site and implemented traffic management measures limiting Bogong - High Plains Road to one lane in this area, with reduced speed also in place.
  • With heavy rainfall forecast for the region this week and into next week,  a full closure of Bogong - High Plains Road will occur for the safety of road users.
  • The closure will be in place from midday on Wednesday 12 October. 
  • During this time access to and from Falls Creek will be allowed for emergency services and essential services only. 
  • When the road will re-open has not been determined and will depend on weather conditions and ongoing management of the landslide risk.
  • Regional Roads Victoria will continue to monitor the landslide risk and potential impact on Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Geotechnical experts will complete assessments of the site and determine the best course of action to address the risk
Stay safe by avoiding fallen trees and powerlines, blocked or damaged roads and the area in general. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide.

A full road closure of Bogong High - Plains Road at Bogong will occur from midday on Wednesday 12 October in anticipation of poor weather worsening the landslide.

Anyone planning to access Falls Creek will need to do so prior to the road being closed and be prepared to stay in the area until the road has reopened. Similarly, anyone planning to leave Falls Creek will need to do so prior to the road closure.

What you should do:
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside during a landside, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, powerlines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Driving:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
  • There will be no access to Falls Creek while Bogong High Plains Road is closed. 
  • The Bogong High Plains Road on the other side of Falls Creek is closed due to snow and will likely remain that way for several more weeks.

Incident Location: Bogong Village and Falls Creek
Issue Date: Tuesday 11 October 2022, 03:47 pm
Next Update: Wednesday 12 October 2022, 03:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/22523/moreinfo

This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek.

- A landslide has occurred on the Bogong - High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
-   There      is a slow moving active landslide on Bogong High Plains Road in the area      near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.  
-   After      recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around      Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto      the Bogong - High Plains Road.  
-   Regional      Roads Victoria has undertaken geotechnical investigations at the site and      implemented traffic management measures limiting Bogong - High Plains Road      to one lane in this area, with reduced speed also in place.  
-   With heavy rainfall forecast for the region this week and into next week,  a full closure of Bogong - High Plains Road will occur for the safety of      road users.  
-   The closure will be in place from midday      on Wednesday 12 October.   
-   During this time access to and from Falls Creek will be allowed for      emergency services and essential services only.   
-   When the road will re-open has not been      determined and will depend on weather conditions and ongoing management of      the landslide risk.
- Regional Roads Victoria will continue to monitor the landslide risk and potential impact on Bogong - High Plains Road.
- Geotechnical experts will complete assessments of the site and determine the best course of action to address the risk


Stay safe by avoiding fallen trees and powerlines, blocked or damaged roads and the area in general. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide. 

A full road closure of Bogong High - Plains Road at Bogong will occur from midday on Wednesday 12 October in anticipation of poor weather worsening the landslide. 

Anyone planning to access Falls Creek will need to do so prior to the road being closed and be prepared to stay in the area until the road has reopened. Similarly, anyone planning to leave Falls Creek will need to do so prior to the road closure.

properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water in the Gippsland Lakes and the Ninety Mile Beach from McLoughlins Beach to Marlo.

  • The levels of blue green algae within the Gippsland Lakes have decreased to well below the safe contact thresholds. The entire Gippsland Lakes system and Ninety Mile Beach is now safe for recreational contact with water.
  • However as toxins from the algae can accumulate in seafood after a bloom has dispersed, advice regarding the consumption of specific seafood still applies.
  • The latest seafood sample results show that Nodularin concentrations remain elevated in crab and bug samples collected within and outside the Gippsland Lakes. Additional seafood samples are being organised for collection and analysis.
Do not consume crustaceans (such as prawns, crabs and bugs) and shellfish caught inside the Gippsland Lakes or within 10 nautical miles of the shore between Mcloughlins Beach and Marlo. 

Finfish caught from within the Gippsland Lakes should be rinsed thoroughly in fresh water and the guts and gills removed before cooking or freezing.

Ingesting these toxins can lead to serious illness. Cooking or freezing does not destroy thetoxins.
What you should do:
  • Visit betterhealth.vic.gov.au (https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/harmful-algal-blooms) for more information.
  • Keep up-to-date with algae information at www.water.vic.gov.au/waterways-and-catchments/rivers-estuaries-and-waterways/blue-green-algae

Protect your health:
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctororNurse-On-Call (https://www2.health.vic.gov.au/primary-and-community-health/primary-care/nurse-on-call)on 1300 606 024.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT CHARLTON TOWN

RENEWED MODERATE FLOODING LIKELY ALONG THE AVOCA RIVER FROM THURSDAY

Minor to moderate flooding is occurring along the Avoca River, with the main flood peak now moving downstream of Charlton Town. 

In the 24 hours to 3:00 pm Tuesday, no significant rainfall has been recorded in the Avoca River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Tuesday. Heavy rainfall is forecast from Wednesday evening and renewed moderate flooding is likely across the Avoca River catchment from Thursday morning.

Avoca River downstream of Charlton Town
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Avoca River Downstream (D/S) of Charlton Town. Further downstream, river level rises are likely at Quambatook in the next few days.

The Avoca River at Quambatook is currently at 1.23 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Avoca River at Quambatook is expected to remain below the minor flood level (2.00 m) during Tuesday into Wednesday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Avoid any contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • If you are camping close to a river or creek, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Main roads, local roads and bridges may be impacted by floodwater.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low-lying caravan parks and camping areas may be impacted by floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
